Cruise Control Sequence Number. The value of CCSequenceNo shall be increased by one and transmitted if BOTH of the following conditions have been satisfied. (i) The A-D conversion and signal conditioning processes have been completed and deemed to be error free. (ii) A calibratable period of time x [where x is 1ms to 255ms] has elapsed since the last CCSequenceNo update. x shall be equal to the period of the LIN Frame which contains the CCSequenceNo, which shall initially be 32ms. The CCSequenceNo shall therefore be incremented by one each time the LIN Frame containing the signal is transmitted, provided that condition (i) above has been satisfied. There should be no two consecutive LIN Frames transmitted which contain the same CCSequenceNo value unless condition (i) is not satisfied

The true scaling factor of this signal is hardware dependant based on the rolling circumference (assumed and actual) and the number of teeth on the wheel speed sensor tooth ring. ODORawCount does not indicate a default condition in the CAN signal. This may be determined from other signals e.g. WheelSpeedFrRQF and WheelSpeedFrLQF.
Rear Wheel Drive and AWD Vehicles (Jaguar X150/X250/X351/X152): --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Raw Rolling Count (counts through zero) of two front wheel speed signals. Measures distance travelled based on a reference circumference of 2.101m and a tooth ring of 46 teeth (AWD vehicles 48 teeth). Calculated by counting both the rising and falling edges of the raw sensor signals from the two front wheel speed signals. Signal increments on average in steps of 11.42mm (AWD vehicles 10.94mm).
Rear Wheel Drive and AWD Vehicles (Jaguar X760/X260/X761): --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Raw Rolling Count (counts through zero) of two front wheel speed signals. Measures distance travelled based on a tooth ring of 48 teeth and a reference circumference of 2.050m (X760), 2.000m (X260) and 2.300m (X761). Calculated by counting both the rising and falling edges of the raw sensor signals from the two front wheel speed signals. On X760, the signal increments on average in steps of 10.68mm. On X260, the signal increments on average in steps of 10.42mm. On X761, the signal increments on average in steps of 11.98mm.
Four Wheel Drive vehicles (Land Rover L319/L320/L322/L405/L494/L462): --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Raw Rolling Count (counts through zero) of two front wheel speed signals. Measures distance travelled based on a reference radius of 0.370m (L319/L322), 0.358m (L320) and 0.380m on L405/L494/L462 and a tooth ring of 48 teeth. Calculated by counting both the rising and falling edges of the raw sensor signals from the two front wheel speed signals. On L319/L322, the signal increments on average in steps of 12.11mm. On L320, the signal increments on average in steps of 11.72mm. On L405, L494 and L462, the signal increments on average in steps of 12.44mm.
Front Wheel Drive and AWD Vehicles (Land Rover L538/L550): --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Raw Rolling Count (counts through zero) of two front wheel speed signals. Measures distance travelled based on a reference radius of 0.359m and a tooth ring of 48 teeth. Calculated by counting both the rising and falling edges of the raw sensor signals from the two front wheel speed signals. Signal increments on average in steps of 11.75mm.

A rolling count (counts through zero) of distance travelled. In steps of 0.000125 miles 00h = 0 miles FEh = 0.03175 miles travelled since last roll-over.

If one wheel speed sensor fails, the speed information from the other sensor is used. If both rear speed sensors fail, the signal defaults.
